Explain the data flow direction in LWC. How does it differ from Aura?
Companies that asked this: Salesforce, Oracle, IBM, Microsoft, Adobe

Answer:
LWC enforces one-way data flow (data down, events up), while Aura supports two-way data binding.

LWC Data Flow (One-Way):

// Parent Component
export default class Parent extends LightningElement {
    @track userName = 'John';
    
    handleUpdate(event) {
        this.userName = event.detail.name; // Parent updates data
    }
}
<!-- Parent Template -->
<c-child name={userName} onupdate={handleUpdate}></c-child>
// Child Component - Read-only properties
export default class Child extends LightningElement {
    @api name;
    
    handleChange() {
        // ❌ Cannot mutate: this.name = 'Jane';
        // ✅ Must fire event up
        this.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('update', {
            detail: { name: 'Jane' }
        }));
    }
}
Aura Data Flow (Two-Way):

html
<!-- Aura - Direct two-way binding -->
<aura:component>
    <aura:attribute name="userName" type="String"/>
    
    <!-- Child can directly modify parent data -->
    <c:childComponent userName="{!v.userName}"/>
</aura:component>

Key Differences:
| LWC                                | Aura                                 |
|------------------------------------|--------------------------------------|
| **One-way:** Data down, events up  | **Two-way:** Direct binding          |
| Child properties are **read-only** | Child can **mutate parent data**     |
| **Predictable** updates            | **Automatic** updates                |
| **Easier debugging**               | **More complex** state tracking      |

Benefits of One-Way Flow:

Predictable - data changes only in parent

Debuggable - clear communication path

Maintainable - prevents unexpected side effects

Interview Tips:

Emphasize "data down, events up" principle

Mention read-only nature of child properties in LWC

Explain that Aura allows direct two-way binding

Highlight debugging and predictability benefits
